messages.msg:
Edmund, you’re completely right.
I doubt there’s any possibility of the general public understanding this stuff.
It would be hard enough even if they wanted to understand it.
But the hard facts are that they’re committed to their Comforting Lies & will block anything which contradicts them.
Thus my target is more informed people. Even then, I’m most unlikely to succeed
Who ever dreamed this up knows that.

Sorry only just seen this. Please avoid embarrassment by referring to hydroxychloroquine and not “hydrochloroquine” which doesn’t exist. Inhaled budesonide now has its own trial, mentioned elsewhere. @yeadon_m’s point about antibodies is important if we are informing the public. But the biggest concern I have with this is that it doesn’t take much notice of disease stage. Covid-19 is clinically peculiar because it can be anything from a sniffle  to fatal. (Successful) clinicians have systematised this by distinguishing viral, early pulmonary, late pulmonary and critical stages etc. The media hysteria is all about late stages with people on oxygen, ventilators etc. The colossal  missing policy element  is arresting development of another coronavirus cold into critical illness. Which can be done by GPs. Prophylaxis is something else again - avoiding getting the infection in the first place. All the supplements (D3, C, zinc, Quercetin) certainly have a role here as in the “outpatient” stages. In fact quercetin is another lacuna; it’s available from nutraceutical outlets and widely recommended as the “poor man’s hydroxychloroquine” because it is a zinc ionophore. Lots of zinc may be a waste of time if it’s simply excreted; it’s intracellular zinc that is needed. Prophylaxis has been shown with ivermectin in an Egyptian RCT of household contacts so the number of index cases plus number of onward infections are both known, so the (prophylaxed) R0 can be numerically estimated. It was 0.3.
Looks good, just suggested a couple of changes.
Bit more than a page - but here's my lateral flow one pager: https://docs.google.com/document/d/1qG16ZQSIU1eE21X8kpr1pQ54Ukt-ipAJD_yLXSzQ_xE/edit?usp=sharing

messages.msg: Yes, I had a discussion with one of my ex-medical student friends who was very worried about antibodies only lasting 3 months (he like me a consultant paediatrician!) , till I reminded him that that is about the half-life of IgG so entirely to be expected. I wish the paper here had included some apparent Covid-naive subjects too

Ros,
This is very good. A few suggestions:
1. emphasise that whether acceptable or remarkable, we UNDERSTAND the risk / benefit associated with use of the drugs you list. That’s not yet true with novel technology vaccines.
2. There have been some clinical trials investigating the effect, if any, of intravenous 
‘convalescent plasma’ (ie. antibodies). I’m not sure that the expected benefits were obtained. This doesn’t surprise me. I’m constantly amazed that even experts, not qualified in immunology, believe that immunity is mostly or wholly conferred by circulating antibodies. It isn’t & we’ve known for a long time that it isn't. Consider this: most of the time, in bacterial infections, the invading organisms are outside our cells because they’re large & easily viewed by light microscopy. Antibodies, once secreted from the B cells which make them, are also large & highly charged species, generally remain outside cells, too. The pathogen & antibodies readily meet-up. But viruses are so small that they’re invisible to light microscopy. Their whole way of replicating requires viruses to enter cells. They’re only briefly outside cells when we first get infected & when infected cells die, spilling the next wave of virus particles. Antibodies & pathogen have very little opportunity to interact. By contrast, we’ve a powerful defence system in cytotoxic T lymphocytes (‘T cells’j. They’re perfectly attuned to detecting virus-infected cells & then kill them. 
I find it so frustrating that people bang on about antibodies & nowadays about so-called ‘immune escape’. The very idea is intrinsically unlikely. If it happened, as a generality, our immune systems would be far less effective than they are!
T-Cell mediated immunity has such diversity that immune escape by a relatively slowly mutating virus is utter nonsense & was shown to be so in a superb recent paper.
Anyway, went on too long, sorry :neutral_face: 
Mike 

[https://www.biorxiv.org/content/10.1101/2021.02.27.433180v1.full.pdf](https://www.biorxiv.org/content/10.1101/2021.02.27.433180v1.full.pdf)

There are published studies that back up his claims. This website should give you enough references and info for a short paragraph https://budesonideworks.com/

messages.msg: If HART is doing a general “here’s the way out” document I believe we need to consolidate the various recommendations and protocols from around the world. We know that IVM+favipiravir is policy in two Indian states; we know that IVM+HCQ is widely practised in Brazil. These are both examples of McCullough’s “dual-antiviral” advocacy. Post-exposure prophylaxis uses just IVM as the anti-viral. I do think the latest evidence on Ivermectin is crucial - IVM+DOXY+Zinc is sold as a “ZIVERDO” pack in India and is basically the “Borody protocol”. The Vitamins (D3+C) are widely available OTC.

messages.msg: I see i mis-typed. Sorry. PROMPT is what I meant. Treatment within the viral/infectious disease, before major pulmonary inflammation has set in. Yes, the most catholic argument (advocated dual anti-virals chosen from HCQ, IVM and favipiravir, plus a “neutraceutical bundle” basically VitD VitC Zinc and quercetin as outlined above) is based on Peter McCullough’s team here https://rcm.imrpress.com/EN/10.31083/j.rcm.2020.04.264
Have you got the PROMPOT references

The huge missing element (as Ros must know from me by now) is simply to treat the disease. The burden must shift away from hospital care back to GPs. The outpatient treatment protocols ALREADY IN OPERATION in many places simply have to be introduced and applied aggressively. By GPs. The spectre lof hospital overwhelm then evaporates. The immune support provided by Vit D is by now a no-brainer, but my family is also taking Zinc, Vit C and Quercetin (a known zinc ionophore) on a daily basis. All fully available from “nutraceutical” outlets. The FLCCC group has published on this and there are other related prophylaxis protocols. Ivermectin prophylaxis is going to be a big deal I am convinced and the only reason for not advocating it from HART right now is that the write-ups are still in progress. But PROMPOT treatment by GPs of all covid-9 cases is I am convinced the missing link.

@willjones1982 I absolutely agree with you. I guess I was trying to tread carefully so as not to get rejected in the first sentence.  If only we'd got in May to get it all pushed out before all the dreaded scare tactics of the latest round of ICU admissions!! Polishing certainly would be needed but not till we've vaguely agreed a strategy we could all get behind. @rosjones Jones

My strategy would be (briefly): self-isolation of the sick (symptomatic); shielding of the vulnerable during the main phase; separate hospital facilities for the infectious as far as possible; improve NHS surge capacity; ensure all good treatments are in play. That's about it (unless I've missed something) - the rest of the socially debilitating and harmful-to-health NPIs that were introduced in 2020 need to be consigned to the dustbin. Don't know what others think?

Thanks Ros. I'd say this document tries to do a lot. It needs references/links to support its various claims. Stylistically it needs polishing I think. In terms of content, I found myself disagreeing with quite a lot - it seems very keen on continuing restrictions given HART's position (as I understand it) that the pandemic is over and we need to get back to normal and stop normalising drastic NPIs, especially a year later.
Yes, would be great if everyone pitches in here, much like mission statement. We need 'forward looking' plans that people can get behind.

Apologies that this is definitely more than one-page! A first stab at an overall 'Plan for Covid'.  Previous groups questioning lockdowns all seem to get rubbished as 'know-alls, what would you do instead?'.  It is very difficult to balance how we encourage people back to normality. All comments, changes v welcome. Definitely should keep this under wraps until anyone important really wants our advice! https://docs.google.com/document/d/1jFTxNbi8SZkepnzleY0UPLYGSbDSlAvnZhM5xoyZJhk/edit
excellent. Thanks Gary.  Just corrected the much   quoted phrase 'don't kill your gran'
Is there a quick way of adding everyone to this channel so they can comment? There are only 7 of us here!
https://docs.google.com/document/d/17v2Bx_-MqxuzrDaj-nOFuj3K9RSbw15ynBIwfKGNtaU/edit?usp=sharing. BIT - psychological damage from gov strategy

Reads well to me, @craig.clare - you’d hope even  MPs would grasp the main points. I know there’s limited space, but wondered whether a specific mention of how the myth of asymptomatic transmission has been used to legitimise the lockdowns & mandatory masks might be included (perhaps in the 1st or last paragraph)? Also a minor typo in first line of 3rd paragraph.
